2025-05-27 02:53:18,476 - INFO - 📌 Category page marked: Spectacular Science & Inventions 🔬 → page 48
2025-05-27 02:53:18,477 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactStory, text='From lightbulbs to lightning-fast rockets, these brainy breakthroughs were discovered on this very date! On this day, brilliant minds made science sparkle and inventions pop!' (page 48)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,477 - WARNING - 🚫 Page 49: No background assigned
2025-05-27 02:53:18,478 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactTitle, text='The Great Comet Race' (page 49)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,478 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactStory, text='In 1577, an incredible visitor blazed across Earth's skies – the Great Comet of 1577! It was like a cosmic celebrity that everyone wanted to spot first. Aztec astronomers in Mexico were the first to record seeing it, followed quickly by stargazers in Italy and Japan just days later. But the real comet champion was a Danish astronomer named Tycho Brahe, who tracked this glowing space traveler for over two months as it zoomed through our solar system! Brahe's detailed observations were super important because they helped prove that comets weren't just weird weather in Earth's atmosphere (as many people thought back then) but actual objects traveling through space. This brilliant, fiery visitor would never return – after saying hello to Earth, it headed off into deep space forever!' (page 49)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,479 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactTitle, text='The Accidental Internet Pioneer' (page 49)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,480 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactStory, text='Born in Taiwan in 1968 and moving to America when he was just 10 years old, Jerry Yang never planned to change the world. While studying at Stanford University, Jerry and his friend David Filo were supposed to be working on their homework, but they got distracted making a list of their favorite websites. This list grew and grew until they created something they called "Jerry and David's Guide to the World Wide Web" - which they later renamed Yahoo! (with an exclamation point for extra excitement!). Their little project exploded in popularity, becoming one of the first major internet companies that helped billions of people navigate the early web. Jerry went from being an immigrant kid who had to learn English to becoming a billionaire tech legend who helped shape how we all use the internet today!' (page 49)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,480 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactTitle, text='From Brain Surgeon to Prime Minister!' (page 49)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,481 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactStory, text='Talk about a super-impressive resume! Ariel Henry from Haiti started out as a neurosurgeon—that's a doctor who performs incredibly delicate operations on people's brains! Imagine having the steady hands and brilliant mind needed to help people with brain injuries or illnesses. But Dr. Henry didn't stop there. He went from healing individual patients to trying to heal his entire nation by becoming a politician and eventually the Prime Minister of Haiti, one of the most challenging leadership jobs in the world. From operating rooms to government offices, Dr. Henry shows that some people have the brains to do it all!' (page 49)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,481 - WARNING - 🚫 Page 50: No background assigned
2025-05-27 02:53:18,481 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactTitle, text='The Luxembourg Sky Mystery' (page 50)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,482 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactStory, text='The Fokker 50, a twin-propeller airplane that looks a bit like a flying bus, was preparing to land at Luxembourg Airport when disaster struck. In difficult weather conditions, the pilots couldn't see clearly, and the plane crashed just short of the runway. Tragically, 20 people lost their lives, while three survivors were pulled from the wreckage. After the crash, air safety investigators—like real-life detectives—studied every piece of the broken plane to understand what happened. Their discoveries led to better training for pilots about flying in bad weather and improvements in airport warning systems. Today, planes have amazing technology that helps them land safely even when pilots can't see the ground clearly.' (page 50)
