2025-05-27 02:53:18,555 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactTitle, text='The Defensive Iceman!' (page 70)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,555 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactStory, text='Brad Stuart, born in 1979 in the snowy land of Canada, became one of ice hockey's most bone-rattling defenders! Imagine being so good at stopping people that you're picked 3rd overall in the NHL draft—that's exactly what happened to Brad in 1998! Throughout his 16-year career, he was like a human wall on skates, making forwards think twice before crossing the blue line. The highlight of his hockey journey? Winning the Stanley Cup (hockey's biggest prize) with the Detroit Red Wings in 2008! Brad skated for six different NHL teams, traveling across North America and blocking thousands of shots. His thunderous body checks became legendary—some say you could hear them all the way up in the nosebleed seats!' (page 70)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,556 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactTitle, text='Brazil's Speed Demon!' (page 70)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,556 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactStory, text='Born in 1978, Zak Morioka wasn't your average kid from Brazil! While most children were riding bicycles, young Zak was already dreaming of Formula racing glory. Starting with go-karts at just eight years old, Zak quickly showed he had a natural talent for speed. By his teens, he was competing in serious racing competitions around the world! Racing through hairpin turns in the Indy Lights series and other championships, Zak broke barriers as one of the few Brazilian drivers to make it big in American racing circuits. His lightning-fast reflexes and fearless driving style made fans hold their breath every time he took to the track!' (page 70)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,557 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactTitle, text='The Joker Who Makes Millions Laugh!' (page 70)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,557 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactStory, text='Born in 1976, Sal Vulcano never imagined that goofing around with his high school buddies would lead to fame and fortune! As one of the four stars of the hilarious TV show 'Impractical Jokers,' Sal and his three best friends since high school (Joe, Murr, and Q) challenge each other to do embarrassing dares in public—and if you refuse, you lose! Despite being afraid of cats, germs, and heights, Sal faces his fears on national television, often ending up in the funniest (and most cringe-worthy) situations. Before becoming famous, Sal worked regular jobs and even has a degree in Finance! His journey shows that sometimes the best career is one where you get paid to laugh with your friends!' (page 70)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,558 - WARNING - 🚫 Page 71: No background assigned
2025-05-27 02:53:18,558 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactTitle, text='The Model Who Became a Superhero' (page 71)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,559 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactStory, text='Rebecca Romijn, born in 1972, has had one of the coolest career transformations ever! She began as a successful fashion model appearing on magazine covers all over the world. Then, in an amazing twist, she became famous for playing Mystique in the X-Men movies—a role that required her to spend HOURS in the makeup chair getting covered in blue paint and scales! Rebecca had to stand perfectly still while special effects artists applied her amazing costume, proving she had superhero-level patience in real life too. Since then, she's starred in many TV shows and movies, showing that you should never limit yourself to just one dream—you can transform your life just like a shapeshifter!' (page 71)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,559 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactTitle, text='The Dark Prince of Gothic Music' (page 71)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,560 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactStory, text='Rozz Williams, born in 1963, wasn't interested in being like everyone else. As a teenager in Los Angeles, he formed a band called Christian Death that would change music forever by helping create a spooky, dramatic style called "deathrock" and "gothic rock." With haunting music, dramatic makeup, and mysterious performances, Rozz became like a dark poet for people who felt different from the mainstream. Beyond music, he was a talented artist who made collages, paintings, and even experimental films. Though he sadly passed away in 1998, his creative spirit lives on through the countless bands and artists he inspired. Rozz showed that being different wasn't just okay—it could be powerful and beautiful!' (page 71)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,561 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactTitle, text='The Musical Chameleon of Texas' (page 71)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,561 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactStory, text='Doug Sahm was like a human jukebox who could play almost any instrument and master any musical style! Born in 1941 in San Antonio, Texas, Doug was a genuine musical prodigy who could play steel guitar, fiddle, and mandolin before he was even 10 years old! As a child, he performed on stage with country music legend Hank Williams Sr. and was offered a permanent spot on the Grand Ole Opry—but his parents thought he was too young! Throughout his amazing career, Doug shape-shifted between rock bands, country groups, Tex-Mex ensembles, and blues outfits. He founded the famous Sir Douglas Quintet and later the Texas Tornados, bringing together different musical worlds and proving that the best musicians don't stick to just one lane—they cruise down every musical highway they can find!' (page 71)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,562 - WARNING - 🚫 Page 72: No background assigned
2025-05-27 02:53:18,562 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactTitle, text='The Split-Jumping Rock Star' (page 72)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,563 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactStory, text='P.J. Proby, born in 1938, wasn't just any singer—he was a rock 'n' roll wild child who shocked audiences with his incredible performances! While other singers just stood at the microphone, P.J. would leap into the air, drop into perfect splits, and keep right on singing without missing a note. His voice could belt out rock songs or croon gentle ballads. In the 1960s, he became super famous in England during the British Invasion (the same time as The Beatles!). But P.J. was actually American, born in Texas! His concerts became legendary when his tight velvet pants would split open during his acrobatic moves—something that scandalized adults but made teenagers cheer even louder!' (page 72)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,563 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactTitle, text='The Frozen Flash on Ice!' (page 72)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,564 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactStory, text='Born in 1981 in Canada (where winter seems to last forever!), Andrew Murray grew up with ice in his veins—but in the coolest way possible! While other kids might complain about the cold, Andrew strapped on skates and turned frozen ponds into his personal playground. His lightning speed and hockey smarts eventually landed him in the National Hockey League, where he played for the San Jose Sharks and other teams. Known for his defensive skills, Andrew was like a hockey superhero whose special power was stopping the other team from scoring! Even when facing the biggest and toughest players in the league, this Canadian ice warrior never backed down.' (page 72)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,564 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactTitle, text='The Soccer Star Nobody Remembers' (page 72)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,565 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactStory, text='Born in 1953, Frank Hanisch was a German footballer (that's what they call soccer players in most of the world!) who played professionally but never became a household name like today's superstars. In the world of sports, for every famous player whose face appears on cereal boxes and billboards, there are thousands of dedicated athletes like Frank who play with heart and skill but don't get the spotlight. Frank's story reminds us that sports history isn't just about the famous few—it's built on the shoulders of countless passionate players who showed up day after day, kicked the ball, defended their goals, and lived for the game, even without the fame and fortune that comes to only a lucky few.' (page 72)
