2025-05-27 02:53:18,738 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactStory, text='These amazing humans didn’t just make a difference — they flipped history upside-down! On this day, they proved that one person really can change the world (and sometimes while wearing a very cool hat).' (page 4)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,738 - WARNING - 🚫 Page 5: No background assigned
2025-05-27 02:53:18,739 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactTitle, text='The Girl with Two Oscars and a Flying Habit' (page 5)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,740 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactStory, text='Sally Field might look like your friendly neighbor, but she's actually a master of transformation with superpowers! Starting as a teenager on TV shows, Sally proved everyone wrong when they said she couldn't be a serious actress. She worked incredibly hard and won not just one but TWO Academy Awards (that's Hollywood's biggest prize!) for becoming completely different characters in the movies "Norma Rae" and "Places in the Heart." She's played everything from a worker fighting for justice to Abraham Lincoln's wife to—get this—a flying NUN in a TV show where she actually wore a habit (nun's outfit) that made her fly when the wind caught it! When she won her second Oscar, she famously exclaimed, "You like me, you really like me!"—words that have become part of American culture.' (page 5)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,740 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactTitle, text='The Rock 'n' Roll Brother Behind the Scenes' (page 5)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,741 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactStory, text='George Young might not be a household name, but this Scottish guitarist and songwriter was the secret weapon behind one of rock's greatest bands—AC/DC! Born in 1946, George first found fame with his own band, The Easybeats, who created the classic hit "Friday on My Mind." But his biggest impact came when his younger brothers Malcolm and Angus formed AC/DC. George stepped behind the scenes as their producer, helping craft their thunderous sound that would rock stadiums worldwide. While his brothers wore the famous schoolboy uniform and performed wild stage antics, George quietly shaped their music, co-writing many early hits and showing that sometimes the biggest influence isn't always the most visible!' (page 5)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,741 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactTitle, text='The Storyteller with Six Strings' (page 5)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,742 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactStory, text='Guy Clark wasn't just a musician—he was a master storyteller who could paint pictures with words and guitar strings! Born in 1941 in Texas, Guy crafted songs that felt like mini-movies about real life, full of characters you'd swear you've met before. His workshop was legendary—not just for making beautiful songs but also for crafting handmade guitars! Artists like Johnny Cash and Kenny Chesney recorded his songs, but Guy never chased fame. Instead, he pursued perfection in his craft, writing classics like "L.A. Freeway" and "Desperados Waiting for a Train." Guy showed that sometimes the most powerful stories aren't told in books or movies but in three-minute songs that can make you laugh, cry, or feel like you've lived someone else's life!' (page 5)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,742 - WARNING - 🚫 Page 6: No background assigned
2025-05-27 02:53:18,743 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactTitle, text='The Little Professor of Soccer' (page 6)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,743 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactStory, text='Johnny Giles might not have been the biggest player on the field, but his soccer brain was GIGANTIC! Born in Dublin, Ireland in 1940, Giles became one of the most intelligent midfielders in soccer history. At just 5'7" tall, he couldn't overpower opponents with size—so he outsmarted them instead! After winning titles with Manchester United, he moved to Leeds United where he formed a legendary partnership with Billy Bremner. Together, they controlled the midfield like chess masters, anticipating moves before they happened! After his playing days, Giles became a manager and then a famous TV analyst known for explaining complicated soccer tactics in ways everyone could understand. For over 30 years, Irish families gathered around their TVs to hear "The Little Professor" break down the beautiful game, proving that in sports, brains can be just as important as brawn!' (page 6)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,744 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactTitle, text='The Judge Who Fought for Fairness' (page 6)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,745 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactStory, text='Leonardo Quisumbing wasn't just any judge—he was a Supreme Court Justice in the Philippines who stood up for what was right, even when it wasn't easy! Born in 1939, Quisumbing started as a brilliant lawyer before becoming the country's Secretary of Labor, where he protected workers' rights. But his biggest impact came when he joined the Supreme Court in 1998. Justice Quisumbing became known for writing clear, powerful decisions that ordinary people could understand—not just other lawyers! He believed courts should protect the "little guy" from powerful interests and governments. In one famous case, he helped protect the rights of indigenous peoples to their ancestral lands. When he passed away in 2019, people remembered him not just as a brilliant legal mind but as someone who used the law as a shield to protect the vulnerable, showing that true justice requires both intelligence AND courage!' (page 6)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,745 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactTitle, text='The Freedom Fighter Who Gave Everything' (page 6)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,746 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactStory, text='Michael Schwerner was born in 1939 and grew up to become a true hero of the Civil Rights Movement. In 1964, during what was called "Freedom Summer," Michael and two other young men went to Mississippi to help register African Americans to vote. This was incredibly dangerous work because many people violently opposed equal rights. Tragically, Michael and his friends James Chaney and Andrew Goodman were kidnapped and murdered by members of the Ku Klux Klan. Their sacrifice shocked the nation and helped push Congress to pass important civil rights laws that changed America forever.' (page 6)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,746 - WARNING - 🚫 Page 7: No background assigned
2025-05-27 02:53:18,747 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactTitle, text='The Home Run Hero Who Broke Barriers' (page 7)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,747 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactStory, text='Born in 1938, Mack Jones was an incredible baseball player who hit powerful home runs that soared over the outfield walls. When he played for the Montreal Expos (Canada's first Major League team), he became so popular that fans nicknamed a section of the stadium "Jonesville" in his honor! But Mack's journey wasn't easy. He played during a time when Black athletes still faced discrimination in sports and society. Despite these challenges, Mack's talent shined through as he played for teams like the Milwaukee/Atlanta Braves, Cincinnati Reds, and Montreal Expos, inspiring a generation of kids who saw him smash those baseballs into the stands.' (page 7)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,748 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactTitle, text='The Doctor Who Never Stopped Learning' (page 7)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,748 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactStory, text='Born in Germany in 1933, Else Ackermann was a superhero of science who never, ever stopped learning! First, she became a medical doctor who treated patients. But that wasn't enough for curious Else! She also became a pharmacologist—a scientist who studies how medicines work in the body. This was during a time when very few women were allowed to be scientists or professors. Else ignored those barriers and blazed her own trail, researching new medicines that could help people with heart problems and other illnesses. Even in her 70s and 80s, when most people are enjoying retirement, Dr. Ackermann was still working in her laboratory, publishing scientific papers, and making discoveries. She lived to be 86 years old, spending more than 60 years solving medical mysteries!' (page 7)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,749 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactTitle, text='The Tiny Particle Hunter' (page 7)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,749 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactStory, text='In 1932, a baby named François Englert was born in Belgium who would grow up to become one of the world's greatest particle detectives! As a physicist, François spent his life hunting for the mysterious Higgs boson—a tiny particle that gives everything mass (which is why you don't float away into space!). For nearly 50 years, scientists weren't sure if this particle even existed! But François and his team developed a theory that proved it was real. In 2012, when François was 80 years old, scientists finally found evidence of the Higgs boson using a massive machine called the Large Hadron Collider. For this amazing discovery that changed how we understand our universe, François was awarded the Nobel Prize in Physics in 2013!' (page 7)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,750 - WARNING - 🚫 Page 8: No background assigned
2025-05-27 02:53:18,750 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactTitle, text='The Laugh-Maker Who Fled the Nazis' (page 8)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,751 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactStory, text='Born in Berlin, Germany in 1931, little Mike Nichols and his family had to flee the Nazis because they were Jewish. Arriving in America speaking almost no English, Mike learned to make people laugh as a way to fit in. As he grew up, he became a comedy star, performing hilarious routines with his partner Elaine May. But Mike's greatest talent was directing—both on Broadway stages and in Hollywood. He created movies that everyone still watches today, like "The Graduate" and "Who's Afraid of Virginia Woolf?" Mike had an incredible gift for telling stories that made people both laugh and think deeply. By the time of his death in 2014, he had won an Emmy, a Grammy, an Oscar, and multiple Tony Awards—one of the few people ever to win all four major entertainment awards!' (page 8)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,751 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactTitle, text='The Professor Who Fought for Fairness' (page 8)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,752 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactStory, text='Born in 1930, Derrick Bell grew up in a time when many Americans were treated unfairly because of their skin color. As a brilliant student, he became the first Black person to be a professor at Harvard Law School—one of the most famous schools in the world! But Professor Bell wasn't satisfied with just being successful himself. He wanted to make sure everyone had equal opportunities. When Harvard wouldn't hire more diverse professors, Derrick did something amazing—he quit his prestigious job in protest! He invented a whole new way of thinking about laws called "Critical Race Theory," which helps people understand how racism can be hidden in rules and systems. Through books, teaching, and brave actions, Derrick Bell spent his life fighting to make America live up to its promise of justice for all people.' (page 8)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,752 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactTitle, text='The Guitar Master of Taiwan' (page 8)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,753 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactStory, text='Born in 1929 in Taiwan, Lu Chao-Hsuan grew up to become the most famous guitarist his country had ever known! At a time when Western music was just becoming popular in Taiwan, Lu mastered the classical guitar and developed a unique style that blended traditional Taiwanese melodies with modern techniques. His fingers could fly across the strings, creating music that made people's hearts soar. But Lu wasn't content just being a star performer—he wanted to share his knowledge with others. He became a beloved teacher who trained generations of guitarists and wrote books about guitar playing that musicians still study today. For nearly seven decades, Lu Chao-Hsuan filled Taiwan with beautiful music until his death in 2017, leaving behind recordings and students who continue his musical legacy.' (page 8)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,754 - WARNING - 🚫 Page 9: No background assigned
2025-05-27 02:53:18,754 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactTitle, text='The Late-Blooming Movie Star' (page 9)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,755 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactStory, text='June Squibb was born in 1929 in Illinois, where she fell in love with acting as a young girl. She spent decades performing in theaters and small TV roles, but most people didn't know her name. Then something AMAZING happened! When June was 84 years old—an age when most people are long retired—she starred in a movie called "Nebraska" that made her famous around the world! She was nominated for an Oscar (one of the biggest movie awards) and suddenly became a Hollywood star in her 80s! Since then, June has appeared in dozens of movies and TV shows, bringing her feisty energy and perfect comic timing to every role. Now in her 90s, June Squibb is still acting and showing the world that it's never too late to chase your dreams and that older people can do extraordinary things!' (page 9)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,755 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactTitle, text='The Joke-Telling Hero of Ireland' (page 9)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,756 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactStory, text='Frank Carson was born in Northern Ireland in 1926 and grew up to become one of the funniest comedians his country ever produced! With his famous catchphrase "It's the way I tell 'em!" Frank could turn any room into a giggling mess. He performed for soldiers during war, entertained royalty, and even when he got older, he never stopped making people laugh. Frank's incredible ability to find humor in everyday life made him beloved across the United Kingdom and Ireland. His jokes and funny stories brought joy during difficult times, proving that laughter truly is the best medicine!' (page 9)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,756 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactTitle, text='The Motivator Who Changed Millions of Lives' (page 9)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,757 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactStory, text='Born in 1926, Zig Ziglar grew up during the Great Depression when his family was so poor they often went hungry. But Zig didn't let his tough start stop him! He transformed himself from a struggling salesman into America's most famous motivational speaker. With his southern accent and unforgettable sayings like "You can have everything in life you want, if you will just help other people get what they want," Zig traveled the world teaching people how to be successful AND kind. He wrote over 30 books that have sold millions of copies, and even when he was in his 80s, he was still inspiring people to be their best selves!' (page 9)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,757 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactTitle, text='The Senator Who Shaped America's Money' (page 9)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,758 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactStory, text='Nelson Aldrich's journey from humble grocery clerk to powerful U.S. Senator is like something from a movie! Born in 1841, this determined Rhode Islander climbed his way up to become known as the 'General Manager of the Nation.' For 30 years, he helped make important decisions about America's money, taxes, and banks. He was so influential that he helped create the Federal Reserve—the super important system that controls America's money to this day! Though some people thought he was too friendly with rich businessmen (his daughter even married into the super-wealthy Rockefeller family!), no one could deny that Aldrich's work completely changed how the United States handles its money forever.' (page 9)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,758 - WARNING - 🚫 Page 10: No background assigned
2025-05-27 02:53:18,759 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactTitle, text='The Musical Inventor Who Changed Music Forever' (page 10)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,759 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactStory, text='Adolphe Sax was a musical mastermind with a wild imagination and incredible determination! Born in Belgium in 1814, he grew up surrounded by musical instruments in his father's workshop. But Adolphe wasn't satisfied with the instruments that already existed—he wanted to create something brand new that would combine the power of brass instruments with the flexibility of woodwinds. After years of tinkering and experimenting, he unveiled his greatest creation in 1846: the saxophone! Despite facing jealous rivals who tried to sabotage his invention and even his workshops, Sax's magnificent instrument survived to become essential in jazz, rock, classical, and pop music. Incredibly, Sax invented not just one saxophone but an entire FAMILY of them, from tiny sopraninos to massive bass saxophones!' (page 10)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,760 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactTitle, text='The Noble Admiral of Venice' (page 10)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,761 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactStory, text='Carlo Aurelio Widmann wasn't just any Venetian—he was nobility from one of Venice's richest and most powerful families! Born in 1750 when Venice was still an independent republic, Carlo grew up in a world of magnificent palaces, gondolas gliding through canals, and powerful merchant ships bringing treasures from distant lands. As he grew older, Carlo followed the tradition of many noble Venetians by becoming an admiral in the famous Venetian navy. He commanded impressive warships that protected Venice's valuable trade routes across the Mediterranean Sea. Sadly, Carlo lived during a time when Venice's power was fading, and just a few years before his death in 1798, the thousand-year-old Republic of Venice fell to Napoleon Bonaparte's conquering French army.' (page 10)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,761 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactTitle, text='The Unlucky King with a Super-Sized Jaw' (page 10)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,762 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactStory, text='Poor Charles II of Spain had one of history's most unfortunate royal lives! Born in 1661 with serious health problems caused by generations of royal relatives marrying their close cousins, Charles had such a massive underbite that he couldn't chew properly and struggled to speak clearly. Despite being ruler of the mighty Spanish Empire—which controlled lands from Europe to the Americas—Charles could barely walk without help and suffered from constant illnesses. Court rumors claimed he was under a witch's spell (earning him the nickname 'El Hechizado'—the Bewitched). The sickly king never managed to have children, and when he died in 1700 at just 38 years old, his death triggered a massive war over who would inherit his throne. Charles was the last of the powerful Habsburg dynasty that had ruled Spain for nearly 200 years!' (page 10)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,762 - WARNING - 🚫 Page 11: No background assigned
2025-05-27 02:53:18,763 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactTitle, text='The Doctor Who Proved Blood Moves' (page 11)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,763 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactStory, text='George Ent was a scientific detective in a time when people still didn't understand how our bodies worked! Born in 1604 in England, Ent became a brilliant doctor and scientist during a revolutionary time when researchers were just beginning to understand human anatomy. His most important work? Helping to prove that blood actually circulates through our bodies—something we take for granted today but was a shocking new idea back then! Ent performed clever experiments and defended his friend William Harvey, who first proposed the theory of blood circulation. Ent's work was so impressive that he was knighted by King Charles II and became a founding member of the Royal Society—the world's oldest scientific organization that still exists today! Without pioneers like George Ent, we might not understand something as basic as how our own hearts work.' (page 11)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,764 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactTitle, text='From Servant to Queen: The Amazing Rise of Karin Månsdotter' (page 11)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,764 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactStory, text='Karin Månsdotter's life reads like a fairytale that actually happened! Born in 1550 to a simple family in Sweden, she began working as a fruit seller before becoming a servant in the royal castle. There, she caught the eye of Prince Erik, who fell madly in love with her despite her humble origins. When Erik became King Erik XIV, he shocked everyone by marrying Karin - making her the first commoner to become Queen of Sweden! Nobles were outraged that a former servant girl could become their queen. Though Erik was eventually overthrown and imprisoned, Karin stayed loyal to him until his death, proving that true nobility comes from character, not birth.' (page 11)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,765 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactTitle, text='Suleiman the Magnificent: The Golden Age Sultan' (page 11)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,765 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactStory, text='Born in 1494, Suleiman became the tenth Sultan of the mighty Ottoman Empire at age 26 and ruled for an incredible 46 years! Under his leadership, the empire reached its golden age, stretching across parts of Europe, Asia, and Africa. But Suleiman wasn't just a powerful conqueror - he was also called 'The Lawgiver' because he completely rewrote the empire's laws to be fairer for everyone. He built magnificent buildings, supported artists and scientists, and even wrote poetry himself! While European kings lived in drafty castles, Suleiman's palace had gardens, libraries, and even indoor plumbing! His reign marked one of history's most spectacular golden ages, where art, science, and fairness flourished together.' (page 11)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,766 - WARNING - 🚫 Page 12: No background assigned
2025-05-27 02:53:18,766 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactTitle, text='Philip the Peacemaker: The Margrave Who Chose Books Over Battles' (page 12)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,767 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactStory, text='Philip I, born in 1479, became the Margrave (that's like a duke or governor) of Baden in Germany when he was just a teenager. While other rulers of his time were obsessed with conquering new lands and fighting wars, Philip made the surprising choice to focus on peace and learning instead! He collected one of the largest libraries in Europe, supported universities, and worked hard to keep his lands out of the many wars sweeping through Germany. During a time when a new religious movement called the Protestant Reformation was causing violent conflicts everywhere, Philip managed to keep his territory peaceful by being fair to everyone. His smart leadership helped Baden grow prosperous through trade and education rather than conquest!' (page 12)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,768 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactTitle, text='The Boy Who Almost Became King: Edmund Mortimer's Wild Story' (page 12)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,768 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactStory, text='Edmund Mortimer, born in 1391, wasn't just any noble kid - he was actually the rightful heir to England's throne according to many people! When he was just 8 years old, King Henry IV seized the crown from Richard II, even though Edmund had a stronger claim by blood. Instead of becoming king, young Edmund became the most dangerous person in England! He was kept under close watch his whole life, sometimes treated like a prince, other times like a prisoner. When he was 11, his uncle tried to kidnap him to start a rebellion! Later, his brother-in-law used Edmund's royal claim to launch the famous Wars of the Roses. Though Edmund himself remained loyal to the kings who ruled instead of him, his royal blood made his very existence a threat to the crown until his death at age 34.' (page 12)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,769 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactTitle, text='K-Pop Superstar: The Rise of Yura' (page 12)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,769 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactStory, text='Born in 1992 in South Korea, Kim Ah-young (better known by her stage name "Yura") danced and sang her way into the spotlight as a member of the popular K-pop girl group Girl's Day. Before becoming famous, she was just a regular kid with big dreams. But after years of intense training—sometimes practicing dance moves for 12 hours a day!—Yura debuted as an idol in 2010. Beyond her singing career, she expanded into acting, appearing in popular Korean TV dramas. Yura's journey shows how dedication, hard work, and following your passions can lead to success in multiple fields!' (page 12)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,770 - WARNING - 🚫 Page 13: No background assigned
2025-05-27 02:53:18,770 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactTitle, text='The Boxing Boy Wonder' (page 13)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,771 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactStory, text='Tony Canzoneri wasn't just any boxer - he was a superstar of the ring during the Great Depression! Born in 1908, this Italian-American fighter stood only 5'4" tall but packed incredible power in his punches. Known for his lightning-fast hands and amazing footwork, Tony became one of the first boxers ever to hold world championships in three different weight divisions at the same time! He fought an incredible 175 professional matches during his career, entertaining crowds across America when people really needed something to cheer about. Even though boxing was a tough sport, Tony was known for being a gentleman outside the ring - proving you can be fierce and kind at the same time!' (page 13)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,771 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactTitle, text='The Voice That Made Radio Famous' (page 13)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,772 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactStory, text='Back in 1900, a baby girl named Ida Lou Anderson was born who would grow up to change how America listened to the radio forever! In a time when women weren't always encouraged to speak up, Ida Lou became one of the first female professors of public speaking and used her incredible knowledge of voice and presentation to pioneer radio broadcasting. She coached famous radio personalities, including Edward R. Murrow, teaching them exactly how to speak so listeners could really feel what they were saying. Her special techniques for speaking on the radio - like how to pause dramatically or emphasize important words - are still used by broadcasters today! Ida Lou helped transform radio from just a technical gadget into a magical storytelling device that could transport listeners anywhere in the world.' (page 13)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,772 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactTitle, text='The Big Train: Baseball's Fastest Pitcher' (page 13)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,773 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactStory, text='Walter Johnson was the most feared pitcher in baseball history! Born in 1887 on a farm in Kansas, Johnson grew up with strong arms from doing chores and discovered he could throw a baseball faster than anyone had ever seen. His fastball was so blazing quick that batters said it looked like just a white blur zooming past them! During his 21-year career with the Washington Senators, the gentle giant set records that seemed impossible - including 417 wins and 110 shutouts (games where the other team couldn't score a single run). What made Walter special wasn't just his incredible arm, but his kind heart. Unlike many fierce competitors, he refused to throw at batters' heads and was known as one of the nicest guys in sports. When he was finally elected to the very first Baseball Hall of Fame class, everyone agreed: no one deserved it more than The Big Train!' (page 13)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,773 - WARNING - 🚫 Page 14: No background assigned
2025-05-27 02:53:18,774 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactTitle, text='The Fearless Hero from Two Countries' (page 14)
2025-05-27 02:53:18,774 - INFO - 🧩 afterFlowable: style=FactStory, text='Martin O'Meara was an ordinary Irish immigrant who became an extraordinary hero! Born in Ireland in 1885, Martin moved to Australia seeking adventure and a better life. When World War I began, he joined the Australian Army even though he wasn't required to fight for his adopted country. During the horrific Battle of the Somme in 1916, something amazing happened - Martin repeatedly ran into no-man's land (the dangerous area between enemy trenches) under heavy machine gun fire to rescue wounded soldiers! Over several days, he saved the lives of 25-30 men who would have otherwise died on the battlefield. For his incredible bravery, Martin was awarded the Victoria Cross - the highest military honor in Australia and the British Empire. Only 64 Australians received this medal during the entire war, making Martin's courage truly exceptional!' (page 14)
